Rather than having the Fed try to dampen asset prices and/or excessive buildups of leverage with rapid rate hikes, and as a result choking off long needed gains in wages, it would be much preferred to have a natural reduction in risk taking from vol induced gross downs.

Certainly not implying a 10% decline in equities to levels from a few months ago has fundamentally changed historically unattractive valuations, but even a quick sharp shakeout serves the purpose of lowering excessive speculation given the amount of money run with vol parameters.

This vol shock and its impact reminded me of  post from a few years ago on the Fed and avalanche patrol. While not perfectly analogous, I am sure the Fed is happy to see leveraged specs shaken out as the rise in vol reduces permitted levels of leverage across strategies.

A month ago, the concerns were high asset prices, complacency moving towards euphoria and dramatically easing financial conditions in spite of the Fed tightening. Combined with still low nominal rates, it was easy to worry about buildups of excessive leverage and risk taking.

I have no idea how to properly dimension the earnings hit they are sure to take, but if you believe that the DTC product succeeds, what do you have to believe for the value it creates to exceed the hit to earnings? Noodling.

That is, why can't DIS continue to license/syndicate content externally while also using it as filler on the DTC service? The original proprietary IP - Lucas, Marvel, Disney etc - will draw customers, so the filler need not be exclusive.

If you believe in the "subs come for original content, and stay for filler view" that NFLX and HBO have proven, seems pretty clear that DIS will be able to acquire customers with their original content. So the question becomes, why does DIS alone have to have exclusive filler?
While the company isn't saying much about the DTC product in light of the FOX merger review, I thought this was a revealing comment, in terms of trying to size the potential earnings hit.
The bear case is that the DTC product is going to create at minimum a $5B drag on earnings, because Disney is going to pull back on licensing/syndication.
And so the core controversy becomes, will the DTC product succeed. And if it succeeds, why will it succeed. IMO, if it succeeds, it will be because Disney IP is best in the world.
So while Disney is still thought of as being a linear TV driven company, turns out that the branded IP part of the company is now larger than the rights aggregator part.

Continuing on Disney. Here's a chart of segment OI since 2001. You can see how powerful a driver of earnings ESPN was through the early 2010s, when it was 60+% of OI. For FY 18, it will be ~30% (excluding the 20% minority interest). Parks + Studios will be ~50% of segment OI.

Recall that Jeff Ubben, who is on the Board of FOX, said he hoped to have Fox "pull an Adobe". They may end up trying to so in sports programming, but clearly Disney is blazing the trail.

DIS is essentially trying to do the on-premise to SAAS shift that Adobe, MSFT et al have done, which involves taking substantial hits to the P/L in order to create long term value via subscriptions. Whether media investors react the same as software investors is an open question.
BTW, here's the original Disney as a Service if you never read it. Holds up well.
And while I'm loathe to make M&A guesses, I do think that DIS is positioning itself to shed a bunch of TV assets over time (asset swap with Comcast for Hulu control? Merge ESPN/ABC and Turner?)
This last point is why, in spite of some aspects of the Fox deal that make sense, by layering in additional linear TV assets, it muddles Disney's otherwise clear pivot away from TV

To the extent that the Disney branded product is successful, it will continue to move more and more of the value away from linear TV, i.e. ESPN/ABC, and change the narrative, and reality!, of Disney as beholden to the bundle.

Everyone frames the Disney branded DTC offering as a "TV" product. But the reality is that Disney's IP is film/studio based, and the service Disney is creating will heavily leverage those assets, not anything to do with TV. It will just happen to be streamed in home to TVs.

Anyway, still find Uber to be one of the most fascinating companies of all time and, having watched Dara for years at Expedia, am very curious to see how he evolves the strategy and what it does to the P/L.

I would've guessed a steady state margin at 15-20%. To get there, need S&M + Support + R&D to be a total of 30-35%. Can't drive R&D much below 10%. So S&M+Support has to = 20-25% total, or Gross Margins have to go way higher than 60%, which seems unlikely given trajectories.

So what I'm saying is I don't understand Uber's expense structure. And it's not "Lol this is a non profit funded by VCs". They obviously have a roadmap to profitability. My question is which expense lines are they going to massively scale. My guess is S&M has to come down to 10%.

Realistically, since I am using a steady state margin, I should use more of a steady state multiple. Let's say 15x. To get to $100B need $6.7B in EBITDA and $95B in revs. $95B in revs is about $450B in gross bookings.  Priceline will do about $110B in gross bookings next year.

Softbank just bought in at ~$50B, they def want to IPO at $100B+. Let's say they get valued at 25x EBITDA, because why not, need $4B in EBITDA. At a 7% margin, that's $57B in revs.  It looks like they will do ~$8B this year.
Support is currently running 18.4% of revs. Say that scales to 10-15%. Gives you a steady state margin of 4.5-9.5% and a midpoint of 7%.

If I close my eyes, I would imagine Uber's expenses as % of revs looks like:  40% COGS 20-25% S&M 10-15% R&D 5-7% G&A  Which results in a 19% margin. But with Operations and Support not accounted for, totally changes steady state margins.

1. Gross margin has deteriorated, opposite of what would expect from scale  2. S&M has leveraged and is about inline with internet cos  3. R&D looks a little high as % of revs  4. G&A hasn't leveraged and is way too high  5. WTF is operations and support and why isn't it in COGS?

You can put them into a spreadsheet side by side, and look at the expense items as a percentage of net revenues to get a sense for evolution of the P/L as Uber gained scale. Obviously a few things jump out.

Getting pushback that WACC should go up with lower tax rates, so I guess I could skip the entire middle section, and say, it this way, ROIC to WACC spread is so wide right now that any viable project is likely being funded. Tax cuts won't change that.

But to summarize, my belief is that the impact of changes in cost of capital on corporate marginal propensity to invest decreases the wider the spread between ROIC hurdles and WACC, and today the spread is already very wide.

Of course it is plausible there are second order impacts. There are efficiency gains from simplifying corp tax code, particularly releasing trapped global income.  And increased divs/buybacks, higher stock prices, etc may cause increased spending leading to more demand.

That is, the gating item to increasing corporate investment today is not cost of capital or access to capital, it is a deficiency of projects meeting return hurdles. Lower tax rates thus lower WACC likely will have little first order impact on this dynamic.

Bloomberg calcs average WACC for the Russell 3000 at 7.9%. Given there is already 200bps and prob closer to 300-400bps spread between hurdle rates and cost of capital, one can conclude that any project corporations believe should be pursued can be funded.

Most operating companies that I‚Äôm familiar with set their investment hurdle rates at a minimum of 10% and mostly in the low double digits, irrespective of their WACC (REITs and other highly levered by nature businesses are an exception).

A significant reduction in corp tax rates reduces WACC, which should significantly increase the marginal propensity to invest. But I am skeptical that at this moment in time that is the case, because I think reality is conditional.
So in theory, if the return of a project is WACC + .01, corporations should pursue it. Thus, even small changes in WACC should yield significant changes in investment by corporations.
Basic finance theory calculates WACC via cost of equity, cost of debt and cap structure. Theory also states that investing where ROIC > WACC is value creating.

A quick stream of conscience on cost of capital, corporate tax rates and the marginal propensity to invest. I assume there is academic literature on the subject but I am removed from those days, and this is based on 15 years of dealing with co‚Äôs.

Tinder's valuation was determined by outside I-Banks. Historically the market has assumed 8-10x sales, but on a much smaller sales number.
If you assume Rad owned around 8-10% of Tinder, you get an implied valuation of $3.5-4B for Tinder.
By next year, you can get Tinder revs of $500M+, approaching 1/3 of all Match revenue.  So what's that worth?
Now, if you assume 2017 avg PMCs of 2.2M, $9/mo ARPU, and 1/3 a la carte, you get revs of about $360M. This is close to 30% of total revs.
On the earnings call, Match CFO disclosed Tinder's "a la carte" revenue, was now 1/3 of direct revenue. This is much bigger than expected.

So two things have happened, the quality of cable nets biz has deteriorated and will continue to, and lesser quality biz have become larger.
As Studio/Parks have grown in % of earnings, the quality of DIS earnings stream has degraded. Studio/Parks are good biz, but not phenomenal.
As for Disney, part of its premium the last 10+ years was that a substantial portion of it's earnings came from a phenomenal business, ESPN.
But, it will have fewer subs, higher price point, higher churn, higher SG&A costs, and be an economically inferior business.
But, important point! Economically worse does not mean the death of ESPN, the implosion of ESPN, or anything else like that.
The simple truth is the linear model was phenomenally good for ESPN. Whatever the future looks like is near certain to be economically worse
